properties.description: The Dry Diggings area is a fascinating area with many signs of gold digging history scattered about. Follow the Goldfields Trail from Daylesford to Castlemaine for an excellent mountain biking adventure, or explore the many 4WD tracks that criss-cross the area. It's very rugged and steep terrain, so be prepared.

It's a bit of a climb up to Beechworth, but the Bridge Rd brewery makes up for it. It's an interesting old town, with lots of interesting architecture, and ye olde tea rooms - or there's always the nearby mountain bike park.

The Old Ocean Rd along the Gellibrand River is a real surprise packet. A mostly flat dirt road that sees almost no traffic, it meanders through oddly shaped hills, lagoons and improbably farmed patches of grass.

After you complete the initial climb from Gisborne, this sealed descent to Bacchus Marsh is a real delight. Long and gentle, you coast seemingly forever with no effort. The real highlight is when the terrain drops away on both sides at once, giving excellent views from your ridgetop position. Even better by moonlight.
Something of an undiscovered gem, this back road into Noojee is perfect for cycle tourists: quiet, gentle gradient, great surface, and surrounded by beautiful bushland.

If there's one thing the Gippsland Plains do well, it's flat. This is a great beginner's rail trail, with towns every few kilometres, not the slightest hint of a hill, and peaceful cycling through relaxing dairy country.
properties.name: Gippsland Plains Rail Trail

properties.description: Gundowring Rd is a gift to anyone riding between Wodonga and Mt Beauty. With only a fraction of the traffic of the busy Kiewa Valley Highway, you can really enjoy the valley scenery, stop to sample a peach at the numerous fruit trees on the way, all without breaking a sweat on the gentle undulations.
One of Victoria's best microbreweries, some of the best vanilla slices, and close to some great cycling in Mt Macedon or Wombat State Forest - Woodend's got cyclists figured out.

It's an odd kind of tourist attraction, but the dramatic cooling towers of Yallourn Power Station are really worth seeing up close. They're massive, and you can get close enough to hear the water rushing down the outside.
properties.name: Yallourn Power Station

properties.description: The Great Alpine Road is great, pretty much all the way from Omeo to Bruthen. Dramatic landscapes, and the gorges of the Tambo River flow on, and on, and on...
There really are not many better lookouts around than Wallace Cragie Lookout on the Barry Way. Hills stretch way into the distance, and you can see the road itself snaking along the hillsides.

The Barry Way/Snowy River Rd may just be Victoria's most epic cycle touring road. 170km separates Jindabye from Buchan, with no towns or services between, along this remote, windy, mostly unsealed, scenic road. With constant undulations rather than massive climbs, the scenery ranges from subalpine farmland through rugged gorges along the Snowy River, through to the stunning rolling green hills near Buchan.

The Jamieson-Licola Rd is an epic journey for the prepared cycle tourist. Mostly dirt, with some corrugations, it features huge climbs, some great scenery south of Mount Skene, and no services of any kind for 90 kilometres.

Rarely does a road so live up to its promise as the Grand Ridge Road. An almost constant panorama surrounds you as you roll up and down lush green countryside. The hills are rarely steep, but the total elevation gains add up. Parts of it are unsealed, and can be rough, so plan ahead.
properties.name: Grand Ridge Road
Walhalla
properties.description: The former gold mining town of Walhalla is a really interesting place to spend an afternoon. No bike shops or breweries, but lots of well maintained old buildings, a gold mine, a lovely pub, great campground and some nice ye olde cafes.

properties.name: Phillip Island Ferry
properties.description: Although it doesn't take cars, the ferry is more than happy to take a few bikes on its trip between Cowes, Stony Point and French Island. It's prone to breaking down, so check on the  day to make sure it's running.

properties.name: Forrest
properties.description: A brewery, a bike friendly cafe, a bike shop, a rail trail, and a great network of mountain bike trails nearby - pretty obvious why you'd want to visit.

properties.name: Goulburn Valley
properties.description: The Goulburn River is a great place for beginning cycle tourists. The gentle terrain mixes riverside vegetation with wineries and farming, and many of the roads are sealed and quiet.

Bright is Victoria's undisputed home of cycle tourism. At the end of the well developed, and sealed, Murray to Mountains Rail Trail, it's got several bike shops, many good cafes and restaurants, and best of all, the renowned Bright Brewery. The swimming hole in the Ovens River is a lovely place to spend an afternoon, after your early morning ride up Falls Creek, Mt Hotham or Mt Buffalo.
properties.name: Bright
Mt Beauty Holiday Centre
properties.description: One of the nicest caravan parks around, with the Kiewa River flowing right past. When you get sick of swimming or tubing, pop over the road for a beer at Sweetwater Brewery.

properties.name: Old Ocean Rd
properties.description: This section of the Old Ocean Rd is a delightful ride through forest and farmland at a perfect gradient. Just make sure you head up to the Glenaire lookout at the southern end on the current Great Ocean Rd.

properties.name: Big River Road
properties.description: The 4-wheel drivers have been keeping this area a secret for years. It's a an adventurous, rugged section of road rising high over the inaptly named Big River. The surface is mostly well graded dirt, but there's a dozen or so kilometres of really rough stuff around Enochs Point. Lots of great camping here.

properties.name: Murchison Gap
properties.description: Not the biggest climb around, but the climb to Murchison Gap is very rewarding. A good surface and a fair gradient, the lookout at the top is the real highlight.

properties.name: Buchan-Orbost Rd
properties.description: A beautiful, winding road through farmland and forest. Great surface, no traffic, easy gradients.

properties.name: Stony Creek Trestle Bridge
properties.description: It would be a real shame to be anywhere in this area and not check out the mighty 250m wooden trestle rail bridge.

properties.name: Mississippi Creek Trail
properties.description: The Mississippi Creek Trail follows an old narrow gauge tramway through lush forest. It's a quite unique experience, with a decent surface and mostly easy grades.

properties.name: Poverty Gully Water Race
properties.description: The Poverty Gully Water Race is a pretty interesting way to experience goldmining history. It's a mountain bike path formed when a water channel was excavated by miners during the gold rush. It's a pretty easy gradient, so you can cruise down all the way into Castlemaine. Take it easy though - there are a few hazards along the path.

properties.name: Mt Buller Village
properties.description: Mt Buller has the best developed mountain biking infrastructure in Victoria. It has two bike shops, a bus shuttle service for cross-country riders, and MTB trails ranging from friendly to scary. And of course it's at the top of an excellent climb, culminating in a very satisfying short walk to the actual summit.

properties.name: Eildon-Jamieson Rd
properties.description: Since it was sealed a couple of years ago, this has quickly become one of the must-do scenic cycling rides. Loosely following the edge of the lake, it features a couple of huge climbs, a very pretty camping area down by Big River, and is surrounded by forest throughout.

properties.name: Cascades Trail
properties.description: A ride down the Cascades Trail is pretty much a necessity for any enterprising bikepacker. The NPWS has actively encouraged mountain bikers to enjoy this great trail, through alpine meadows, clear streams, rough ridges and brumby country. A couple of historic huts really cap things off. At the border, either press on naughtily, or face a massive slog back uphill.

properties.name: Licola Rd
properties.description: The Licola Rd is probably just too far from anywhere for many cyclists to bother, but it's a beauty. A series of climbs takes with the odd panoramic vista take you through different gorges of the Macalister River until the paddocks around Licola unexpectedly appear. Watch out for caravans on the windy sections.

properties.name: Wonangatta Road
properties.description: The Wonangatta Valley is one of those places most people have no reason to ever visit but would be glad if they did. It's a magical, remote place that feels very disconnected from anywhere. The dirt road rises up and down along the sides of the valley, improving steadily as you approach Dargo.

properties.name: O'Shannassy Aqueduct Trail
properties.description: There's not much to compare this trail to. It's wide like a dirt road, but closed to vehicles, is gentle sloping, but requires an epic climb to get to in most places, and it doesn't really go anywhere. But the bush surrounds are nice and the surface is good, so it's worth a detour.

properties.name: Carriage Cafe
properties.description: Carriage Cafe is one of those places that became an instant favourite. A converted train carriage, right on the rail trail, it always seems to entice even the most faff-resistant cycle tourists to take a moment.

properties.name: Mt Macedon
properties.description: It's steep and it's tough, but the climb isn't so long, and the views are magnificent from the top. There are several entertaining ways down.

properties.name: Byer's Back Track
properties.description: An old water race hacked out of the hillside, this is now a fascinating cliff-top mountain bike ride. Take it slow, and walk any sections you're not comfortable with.

properties.name: Mt Buninyong
properties.description: The easy climb up "Mount Bunny" is used as a criterium circuit for road cyclists. There's a good view from the observation tower at the top, after you negotiate the unique double-spiral road design.

properties.name: Western Port Bay Trail
properties.description: The Western Port Bay Trail is an excellent sealed bike path taking you all the way from Somerville through Hastings and the Warrangine Park coastal reserve to Balnarring. It almost, but doesn't quite, connects with the Red Hill Rail Trail and the Baxton-Frankston bike path.

properties.name: Timboon
properties.description: Timboon is the delightful end of the Camperdown-Timboon Rail Trail. Nestled in a particularly nice bit of forest, it's got a distillery/cafe, a couple of shops, and nice places to just hang out and contemplate your next adventure.

properties.name: Barwon Heads
properties.description: If ever there was a town where you'd feel comfortable walking around in knicks, it's Barwon Heads. Home of Cadel Evans and seemingly thousands of road cyclists, it's got more cafes, bars and yuppy delights than you can poke a stick at. The river is very pretty, and there are lots of good day trips, such as Torquay, Point Lonsdale, or even Anglesea.

properties.name: Skyline Rd
properties.description: There are two ways back to Melbourne from the Yarra Valley: the easy way, and Skyline Rd. The heart-starting sealed climb is quickly followed by a series of unsealed undulations with great views over the valley. You'll be glad you did.

properties.name: Dead Horse Gap
properties.description: You won't forget the climb up to Dead Horse Gap in a hurry. From the beautiful Murray at Tom Groggin, the climb begins abruptly and never really lets up, hovering around 8%.

properties.name: Mt Kosciuzko
properties.description: Australasia is the only content whose highest point can feasibly, if not quite legally, be climbed on a bicycle. If you get there very early, you can beat the first daytrippers coming up from Thredb.

properties.name: Mt Baw Baw
properties.description:
There are few climbs in the world, let alone Australia, like the gruelling ascent of Mt Baw Baw. Gaining just shy of 1000m, around half of it is over 11% - that's nearly double other Alpine roads such as Falls Creek. The steepest sections are over 20%. Take care, and the lowest gears money can buy.
The views from the top are kind of meh, and it's a decent hike to the true summit. Even more annoying, there's no way forward but back down - but that's not why you came here.

properties.name: Acheron Way
properties.description: If the Acheron Way was sealed, the road cyclists would be all over it. Quiet, flat and sealed to begin with, the road passes through beautiful forest, before climbing steadily up around the side of Mt Donna Buang. The unsealed section is a bit sandy and gravelly in parts, but shouldn't cause any major issues.

properties.name: Tarago Rd
properties.description: Tarago Rd makes a nice change from the busy sealed roads in this area. Take a quiet ride on a dirt road through Bunyip State Forest, meandering across numerous creek crossings with no strenuous climbs.

properties.name: Bass Valley Road
properties.description: A delightful surprise, this flat, shady valley is a nice change from the exposed hills, on a sunny day. Never far from the creek, the road makes the most of one of the few patches of native forest remaining in this part of Gippsland.

properties.name: Strathbogie-Merton Rd
properties.description: This short but sweet unsealed road is a nice way to descend the Strathbogie plateau. Good surface, easy gradient and pleasant winding through the bush.

properties.name: Ennis Rd/Fairview Rd
properties.description: The climb up and over the Tallarook State Forest plateau is a startlingly beautiful ride, winding its way up through granite boulders and stunted trees to a ridge with excellent southerly views. Partly unsealed, the road is very quiet, other than the odd 4WD.

properties.name: Dargo High Plains Road
properties.description: The Dargo High Plains Road is one of the great adventures of Victorian cycle touring. From Dargo, the road climbs and climbs, an aggressive gradient leaving little chance to admire the sweeping panoramas to your right. To make things harder, it gets unsealed, before easing off into a long winding forest section, before hitting the flat "high plains" proper. The first views of Hotham are magnificent, as are the winding descents past favourite 4WD territory such as Blue Rag Range. It's hard, it's long, but you'll be so glad you did it.

properties.name: Murray River Road
properties.description: From the Hume Dam to the hydro town of Khancoban, this journey along the upper reaches of the Murray River is touched by hydroelectricity. It's a beautiful place, with soft landscapes, wide floodplains and majestic redgums. There are few major hills, and few still towns along the way - no wonder Walwa's general store cafe is such a popular place.

properties.name: Spring Drive
properties.description: This stretch of Murray cycling has a few things going for it: moderate traffic, good shoulders, and intermittent glimpses of the Murray suddenly opening up to the eerie sight of thousands of dead trees in Lake Mulwala.

properties.name: Wunghnu
properties.description: You've likely never heard of the tiny town of Wunghnu (pronounced "one-ewe" - leading to a classic sheep joke), but make an effort to spend an evening at its pub, the Innstitute Tavern. A lot of local character has turned this old Mechanic's Institute into a very quirky pub, with lots of in-jokes, odd signs and curios festooned around the walls. Plus, the port is cheap.

properties.name: Ghin Ghin Rd/Highlands Rd
properties.description: The unheralded Ghin Ghin Rd quickly rises to a spectacular position over the landscape, working its way steeply through a narrow pass to a beautiful vantage point. Then, heading towards Seymour, roll down the ridge, twisting down through granite boulders and pretty bushland.

properties.name: Tarra Valley Road
properties.description: The Tarra Valley Road is a real treat. A narrow asphalt road that twists frequently as it traces the contours of the creek, it seems to have been tailor-made for cyclists. The descent through ferntrees and lush rainforest is nothing short of exhilarating, and the campground at the bottom is in a magical spot. Well worth the detour from the Grand Ridge Road, or continue down to Port Albert on the Tarra Trail..

properties.name: Traralgon-Balook Rd
properties.descriptin: The ride over Mt Tassie has much the same character as the Grand Ridge Road: constant undulations, great views, and a huge climb or descent on the Traralgon side.

properties.name: Domino Trail
properties.description: Not your average rail trail, the Domino Trail is half meandering dirt track through muddy forest, and half elevated rail trail on an impressive embankment.

properties.name: Tamboritha Road
properties.description: The Tamboritha Road may be the biggest climb you've never heard of. A gentle sealed meander through the popular campsites of the Wellington valley give way to a more determined climb. From the Lake Tali Karng it's all unsealed, winding through numerous cuttings until the beautiful alpine plateau is reached, 1300m in total.

properties.name: Murray to Mountains Rail Trail (Beechworth branch)
properties.description: Uphill or down, the Beechworth branch of the Murray to Mountains Rail Trail is one of the nicest stretches of rail trail around. Alternating serious embankments with deep cuttings, the constant grade doesn't muck around, but you've got a great brewery to look forward. On the descent, mix things up with the mountain bike trail running on your left through the middle section.

properties.name: Bendigo
properties.descriptin: Bendigo has done a lot for cyclists. The O'Keefe Rail Trail begins here, reaching Heathcote by the end of 2014, and one day Heathcote Junction. The Bendigo Bushland Trail makes a beautiful circumnavigation of the town's outskirts, and the Goldfields Trail gives an awesome mountain bike journey from here to Bunyinong. Throw in some well defined road routes, lots of interesting historical sites to explore, and great terrain for mountain biking, and be patient that a microbrewery might one day open up.
